3. Reverence. This is twofold; Spiritual, and Corporal. The Spiritual is an awful and dreadful apprehension of the heavenly Majesty of God before whom we present our selves: and is necessary in regard of that infinite disproportion which is betwixt God and us: He, the Great and glorious God of heaven and earth; We, dust and ashes;
Psal. 2.11 He, the Creator; We, the poore Creatures. Therefore ought we to serve him with fear, and rejoyce with trembling. We must take heed that we be not surprized with such heedlesness, as to say with Jacob, Gen. 28.16. Surely the Lord is in this place, and we know it not, but

to remember what he said upon his better thoughts, How dreadful is this place, this is none other but the house of God. And if Iosephs brethren were afraid, being brought into Iosephs house, Gen. 43 18. We, upon due consideration of our selves, have more cause to feare, when we come into the house of God.

Adoration, which, as it was the Aspha, so, if we make it the Omega of our service, no doubt but God will be pleased with it. Humbly on and rudely off, suits not with the dignity of a great man; much lesse with the Majesty of the great God of heaven and earth. Nor is this a new thing, that it should be attached for an innovation: for it was practised in the dayes of king Hezekiah, in that famous solemn sacrifice, 2 Chron. 29.28, 29. when, both the King, and the congregation worshipped at the beginning and end of the sacrifice: which, how convenient and commendable it is to be still practised by our Christian assemblies in Gods house, to the honour of God;
Constitut. & Can. of 1640. Can. 7. may appear by the judgement and joynt consent of many reverend and learned men convened together: who
(to use their owne words, which reach higher then their own times) thought it very meet and behoovfull, and heartily commending it to all good and faithfull people, members of this Church, that they be ready to tender unto the Lord the said acknowledgement, by doing reverence and obeysance, both at the comming in, and going out of the said Churches, Chancels, or Chappels, according to the most ancient custome of the Primitive Church, in the purest times, and of this Church also for many years of the raign of Queen Elizabeth. Seeing then; there is evidence for an after-adoration to be performed unto God, and hothing materiall to be said against it; Why may we not, nay, Why should we not practise it, when we go out of Gods house? This our egress may (not improperly) be termed the foot of our service, and therefore we ought to take heed to it, as to our foot; in the more proper sense of the text.
